  "doc_id": "13731",
  "text": "For our analysis we used the 195 nt Azoarcus sp. bacterial group I ribozyme because it has a stable tertiary structure [CITATION_1] and well-characterized equilibrium folding pathway ( Figure 1A ) . In 0.2-0.4 mM Mg 2+ , assembly of the core helices produces native-like intermediates (I C ) that are almost as compact as the native ribozyme [CITATION_2] . The I C intermediates are stabilized by tertiary interactions [CITATION_3] ), but the tertiary contacts between double-helical domains are not fully stable, as judged by hydroxyl radical footprinting of the RNA backbone . Local reorganization of the tertiary structure in 2-4 mM Mg 2+ yields the fully folded and catalytically active native state (N) . These folding transitions are well separated and can be distinguished by different experimental assays. We mutated five tertiary interaction motifs singly and in combination, avoiding active site residues and mutations likely to change the secondary structure of the RNA. Single-base substitutions were designed to disrupt the joining region J2/3, the central triple helix (TH), and paired region P6 within the ribozyme core, and two peripheral tetraloops (TLs) L2 and L9 that dock with helical receptors (TR) in P8 and P5, respectively (Figures  1B and 1C; see Table S1 available online for details). The single-base substitutions were combined in six double mutants, four triple mutants, and one quadruple mutant to measure the thermodynamic cooperativity between tertiary interaction motifs in different regions of the RNA.",
